The Setup
Project: Penguin-barn training pipeline — training a robot navigation policy using ReinFlow (flow-matching based online RL) on top of a pretrained IQL checkpoint. 20 actors run in Singularity containers collecting experience, one GPU learner trains the policy.
Hardware: AMD Threadripper 2990WX (32 cores), RTX 2080 Ti (11GB), 80GB RAM
Goal: Train to 2,000,000 gradient steps by April 7 for April 8 submission.

Issue 1: 2990WX NUMA Architecture Problem
Problem: The Threadripper 2990WX has 4 dies but only 2 have memory controllers. Actors landing on compute-only dies (1 and 3) suffer 2-3× memory latency.
Evidence: ps aux showed two clear tiers — actors 0-10 using 88-114% CPU, actors 11-19 using 155-173% CPU for identical work.
Fix: Recommended numactl --cpunodebind=0,2 --membind=0,2 to pin learner to memory-attached dies. Applied to learner launch command.

Issue 2: The Main Killer — buffer_refresh_steps: 1000 + 20,770 Files on Spinning Disk
Problem: This was the catastrophic issue that wasted 24 hours. The config had buffer_refresh_steps: 1000, meaning every 1,000 gradient steps the learner called load_all_buffer_files() which did torch.load() on every single .pt file in the buffer folder. After 24 hours there were 20,770 files totalling 57GB on a spinning disk (sdb). Each reload cycle took 8-15 minutes. The learner trained for ~2 minutes then waited 15 minutes, repeated forever.
Evidence:

iostat showed sdb at 50-84% utilization constantly
GPU at only 30-40% utilization
ls local_buffer/*.pt | wc -l returned 20,770
du -sh local_buffer/ showed 57GB
After 24 hours fewer than 5,000 actual gradient steps completed

Fix: Three-part solution:

Changed buffer_refresh_steps: 1000 → 50000 in config
Purged old buffer files keeping only newest 3,000: ls -t local_buffer/*.pt | tail -n +3001 | xargs rm -f
Moved buffer to RAM: sudo mount -o remount,size=20G /dev/shm && cp -r local_buffer/ /dev/shm/local_buffer/


Issue 3: Zero Checkpoints Saved in 24 Hours
Problem: train.py saved checkpoints to buffer_path (originally local_buffer/). When buffer was moved to /dev/shm/ (RAM), checkpoints would save there and be lost on crash/reboot. Also explained why no checkpoints existed — the learner barely hit 5,000 steps so save_every: 5000 never triggered.
Evidence: find / -name "*.pt" -newer checkpoints/iql_model_node_ready.pt returned nothing outside local_buffer. Only one checkpoint existed: the original iql_model_node_ready.pt.
Fix: Patched train.py to hardcode checkpoint saves to checkpoints/ folder:
bashsed -i 's|policy_path = os.path.join(buffer_path,|policy_path = os.path.join("checkpoints",|g' train.py
sed -i 's|ckpt_path = os.path.join(buffer_path,|ckpt_path = os.path.join("checkpoints",|g' train.py
Also changed save_every: 5000 → 1000 for more frequent saves.

Issue 4: No Training Log — Learner Output Lost Forever
Problem: The original run_all.sh ran the learner with output going only to the terminal. No persistent log file existed. Could never check learner status without being at that exact terminal.
Fix: Added 2>&1 | tee logs/train.log to learner launch command. Output now goes to terminal AND file simultaneously. Monitorable from any terminal with tail -f logs/train.log.

Issue 5: /dev/shm Would Fill Up and Crash Everything
Problem: After moving buffer to RAM, actors continuously write new episode files to /dev/shm/local_buffer at ~20 files/minute. With 20GB mounted, this would fill up in 4-6 hours and crash the learner.
Fix: Cleanup loop running in Terminal 4:
bashwhile true; do
    COUNT=$(ls /dev/shm/local_buffer/actor_*.pt 2>/dev/null | wc -l)
    if [ $COUNT -gt 3500 ]; then
        ls -t /dev/shm/local_buffer/actor_*.pt | tail -n +3001 | xargs rm -f
        echo "$(date): Trimmed to $(ls /dev/shm/local_buffer/actor_*.pt | wc -l) files"
    fi
    sleep 600
done

Issue 6: Gazebo Crashing Inside Singularity — GLX/Rendering Errors
Problem: After the buffer was moved to RAM and actors were relaunched, Gazebo crashed immediately with:
