We tried RAM but hit a Singularity bind mount problem.
When we launch actors with:
bashsingularity exec -B ${buffer_path}:${buffer_path}
This tells Singularity to mount the host path ${buffer_path} into the container at the same path. But /dev/shm is a special RAM-backed filesystem — Singularity doesn't bind mount it the same way as regular directories. The actors inside the containers couldn't see or write to /dev/shm/local_buffer/, so they fell back to writing to disk local_buffer/.
Does it matter now?
Honestly, much less than before because:
BeforeNowReload every 1,000 stepsReload every 50,000 stepsReload ALL 20,770 filesReload only NEW files (incremental)15 min reload freeze~30 second reload every few hours
